to see if there's a fault line?

315
00:20:29,900 --> 00:20:31,800
- No, let's do it your way.
- My way?

316
00:20:31,800 --> 00:20:35,700
- We'll empty every building over two storeys.
- God, you're a geek.

317
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:37,700
- Mike, Emmit.
- You're a geek.

318
00:20:37,900 --> 00:20:39,500
Nice shirt, Stan.

319
00:20:40,500 --> 00:20:42,000
You Roark? Amy Barnes.

320
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:44,800
- Hi.
- I'm from CIGS. Nice to meet you.

321
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:48,400
Careful not to disagree
with anything Dr Barnes says.

322
00:20:48,600 --> 00:20:52,300
Would you give it a rest? All we said was
Cahuenga was geologically unstable.

323
00:20:52,600 --> 00:20:55,800
- The whole city is.
- That's why we don't want tunnels blown up.

324
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:59,200
Thanks for coming on short notice,
but save the fight for later.

325
00:20:59,500 --> 00:21:01,400
Sure. Two o'clock good for you?

326
00:21:03,700 --> 00:21:05,600
- Huh?
- Go ahead. Encourage her.

327
00:21:07,600 --> 00:21:10,300
Dr Barnes, can you tell me
what's under MacArthur Park?

328
00:21:10,500 --> 00:21:12,000
Not with any certainty, no,

329
00:21:12,200 --> 00:21:14,100
- That's a shock.
- but l...

330
00:21:14,300 --> 00:21:16,800
We ran trains through all day. No incidents.

331
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:21,600
This analysis from the guys
who collapsed Hollywood Boulevard.

332
00:21:21,900 --> 00:21:25,800
My engineers were there - no demonstrable
risk. You got conflicting evidence?

333
00:21:26,100 --> 00:21:28,900
Some reason to strand passengers?
I'm all ears.

334
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:31,700
Until then, we stay on schedule.

335
00:21:31,900 --> 00:21:33,700
I'm sorry, Mike.

336
00:21:35,200 --> 00:21:36,900
Oh, lah!

337
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:38,700
He's gotta change his nicotine patch.

338
00:21:41,700 --> 00:21:42,800
- So?
- So.

339
00:21:44,400 --> 00:21:49,200
So? How do I find out
what's underneath MacArthur Park?

340
00:21:49,400 --> 00:21:51,900
..low-grade evacuation ofMacArthurPark.

341
00:21:52,200 --> 00:21:56,200
City officials won'tsayif
it has anything to do with the deaths today

342
00:21:56,300 --> 00:21:58,100
of those seven public workers.

343
00:21:59,800 --> 00:22:03,000
Take a look at this.

344
00:22:03,200 --> 00:22:05,200
OK. Um, what am I looking at?

345
00:22:06,800 --> 00:22:09,700
That lake was 62 degrees yesterday.
Today it's up to 68.

346
00:22:09,900 --> 00:22:12,500
- Yeah, it's a sunny day.
- It is lovely, isn't it?

347
00:22:13,400 --> 00:22:18,300
It takes a geological event to heat a million
gallons ofwater by six degrees in 12 hours.

348
00:22:18,600 --> 00:22:20,100
What is a geological event?

349
00:22:21,400 --> 00:22:25,400
I'm sure you're aware of this,
that our continents sit on tectonic plates.

350
00:22:25,600 --> 00:22:28,300
- Great big rafts on an ocean of molten rock.
- Yeah.

351
00:22:28,600 --> 00:22:32,800
When they shift, like they did this morning,
we get an earthquake. OK?

352
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:34,900
Yeah.

353
00:22:35,100 --> 00:22:38,800
Same mechanism
can sometimes open a fissure, sometimes.

354
00:22:39,100 --> 00:22:43,700
Magma can find
one of those fissures and rise up through it.

355
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:44,900
What's magma?

356
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:48,300
- Lava.
- Lava? Uh, here in LA?

357
00:22:49,600 --> 00:22:51,100
It's one of several possibilities.

358
00:22:52,300 --> 00:22:54,500
It is unlikely, but it is a possibility.

359
00:22:54,700 --> 00:22:57,100
We have a history of that
in the downtown area?

360
00:22:57,300 --> 00:23:02,300
Paracutin, 1943, a Mexican farmer
sees smoke coming out of his cornfield.

361
00:23:02,700 --> 00:23:05,400
A week later there was a volcano 1,000ft high.

362
00:23:05,600 --> 00:23:09,000
There's no history of anything
until it happens, then there is.

363
00:23:10,600 --> 00:23:11,800
Well, thanks, ladies.

364
00:23:11,900 --> 00:23:13,600
Um,

365
00:23:13,800 --> 00:23:15,600
enjoy your day in the park.

366
00:23:17,500 --> 00:23:21,300
- Ooh, yeah, that was subtle.
- What? You want me to humour him?

367
00:23:21,500 --> 00:23:24,600
He asked us for a hypothesis.
You have a better one?

368
00:23:24,900 --> 00:23:26,200
It's lava.

369
00:23:26,200 --> 00:23:27,300
Lava, hm.

370
00:23:27,600 --> 00:23:30,500
Hey, hey, that's me!
My God, I'm gonna call my mom.

371
00:23:30,700 --> 00:23:32,900
- Uh-huh.
- I'm on the TV, man!

372
00:23:34,500 --> 00:23:35,400
Excuse me.

373
00:23:35,400 --> 00:23:37,400
You invited us, remember?

374
00:23:37,600 --> 00:23:41,100
You want me to call Olber
and tell him the demonstrable risk is lava?

375
00:23:41,400 --> 00:23:44,700
- Just give me time to do my work.
- Cos a lake went up a few degrees?!

376
00:23:44,900 --> 00:23:48,200
No, because seven men baked to death
and nobody knows why.

377
00:23:48,400 --> 00:23:50,200
MTA does not answer to the city.

378
00:23:50,400 --> 00:23:53,600
I cannot go to the mat with them
unless you know something.

379
00:23:53,900 --> 00:23:55,200
I do know something,

380
00:23:55,300 --> 00:23:57,000
just not with any certainty.

381
00:23:58,500 --> 00:23:59,900
Is that the company line?

382
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:02,400
I'm a scientist. Certainty is a big word.

383
00:24:02,500 --> 00:24:06,200
I need time to collect my data.
I've gotta get down there and get samples.

384
00:24:06,500 --> 00:24:08,200
- I can't let you do that.
- Why not?

385
00:24:08,400 --> 00:24:10,400
It is too dangerous.

386
00:24:10,500 --> 00:24:11,600
That's why.

387
00:24:12,300 --> 00:24:14,300
I'm sorry.

388
00:24:22,600 --> 00:24:23,900
Shit.

389
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:25,000
What did he say?

390
00:24:25,200 --> 00:24:28,000
Oh, it's too dangerous.

391
00:24:28,200 --> 00:24:31,700
It's man's work and you're girlies.
I can't let you go down there.

392
00:24:31,900 --> 00:24:34,100
- He likes you. I can tell.
- He's OK.

393
00:24:34,300 --> 00:24:39,500
In a macho, controlling, "suspicious of
anyone not from his home town" kinda way.

394
00:24:39,900 --> 00:24:41,900
So you like him. This is good.

395
00:24:43,800 --> 00:24:45,400
We've got to go down there.

396
00:24:45,600 --> 00:24:48,500
I don't see how we can.
This place is swarming with cops.

397
00:24:48,600 --> 00:24:49,600
Yeah.

398
00:24:49,900 --> 00:24:53,000
Let's do it in the morning
before the cops come on duty.

399
00:24:53,200 --> 00:24:55,500
All right. I'll pick you up at four.

400
00:24:55,700 --> 00:24:58,500
Four it is. Bring coffee. What have you got?

401
00:24:58,700 --> 00:25:00,700
More harmonic tremors.

402
00:25:26,300 --> 00:25:28,800
Good morning. It'sjustafter5.10.

403
00:25:28,900 --> 00:25:31,700
Didn't take long
to get ourfirstalert this morning.

404
00:25:31,900 --> 00:25:37,000
A jack-knifed truck on the westboundside
of the 10 is spreading tomatoes everywhere.

405
00:25:37,300 --> 00:25:38,500
One lane open...

406
00:26:19,300 --> 00:26:21,100
Wow.

407
00:26:22,400 --> 00:26:24,800
Earthlings, we come in peace.

408
00:26:27,700 --> 00:26:31,200
God, these suits weigh a ton.
I feel like I'm wearing a car.

409
00:26:31,500 --> 00:26:32,900
Hey, look at this.

410
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:35,100
- What's that?
- Looks like sulphur.

411
00:26:35,200 --> 00:26:37,600
I can't smell it.

412
00:26:37,800 --> 00:26:41,600
- Ah, shit! My flashlight's going out.
- It's everywhere.

413
00:26:41,900 --> 00:26:44,700
Could be traces of magnesium, nickel.
What d'you think?

414
00:26:44,900 --> 00:26:47,200
Take some samples. That's how we'll find out.

415
00:26:47,400 --> 00:26:50,300
My battery's dead. Hold on a sec.

416
00:26:50,600 --> 00:26:52,200
Hey?

417
00:26:55,100 --> 00:26:57,200
What? What you got?

418
00:27:00,700 --> 00:27:03,100
I don't know.

419
00:27:45,100 --> 00:27:47,100
Daddy!

420
00:27:48,100 --> 00:27:49,000
Kelly, baby!

421
00:27:49,100 --> 00:27:50,100
Kelly!

422
00:27:52,500 --> 00:27:53,500
Dad!

423
00:27:54,600 --> 00:27:56,600
Hang on, baby!

424
00:27:57,300 --> 00:28:00,300
Come on, sweetie.
Back! Get under the door frame.

425
00:28:03,900 --> 00:28:04,900
Oh, God!

426
00:28:22,200 --> 00:28:22,700
Rachel?

427
00:28:24,100 --> 00:28:26,100
Amy! Argh!

428
00:28:27,600 --> 00:28:30,000
Help! I've got...

429
00:28:30,200 --> 00:28:32,000
Amy! Amy!

